{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516016"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:37:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:37:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12545"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12545"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.2,0.08,0.56,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5044"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114975"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5044"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12545"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96981"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1635"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"6555"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8392"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8414"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48589"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114975"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old male presents to the emergency department with sudden onset of severe sharp chest pain radiating to his back. The pain is not pleuritic and has been gradually worsening over the past hour. It is associated with dyspnoea and pre-syncope. He has no cough, headache, or nausea. He has travelled back from New Zealand on a plane one week prior. His past medical history includes hypertension and Marfan syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 180/100mmHg and he is tachycardic at 120bpm. Radio-radial delay is present. Heart sounds are dual with no additional sounds or murmurs. Bronchovesicular breath sounds are present. He has no neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis ECG shows sinus tachycardia. Investigations are unremarkable apart from a troponin of 20 (\u0026lt;5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of one the following medications should be initiated immediately?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspirin","Nitroglycerin (GTN)","Heparin","Beta-blocker","Calcium channel blocker"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with aortic dissection. This is a life-threatening emergency that requires prompt diagnosis and management. Patients with known risk factors such as hypertension, Marfan syndrome, and a previous history of aortic aneurysm are at higher risk for aortic dissection. The Stanford and Debakey classifications are the two main anatomic classifications to classify aortic dissection. This patient requires an urgent CT aortogram. The immediate management of suspected aortic dissection involves reducing blood pressure and heart rate to decrease the shear forces acting on the aorta. The most appropriate medication to initiate is a fast-acting \u003Cstrong\u003Ebeta-blocker,\u003C/strong\u003E such as labetalol, as it reduces heart rate and blood pressure, thus preventing extension of the aortic dissection. If the aortic dissection extends into branches of the aorta (e.g. coronary arteries, aortic root), severe complications such as myocardial infarction or aortic regurgitation can occur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for the immediate management of suspected aortic dissection as it can increase the risk of bleeding. \u003Cstrong\u003EHeparin\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended for the acute management of aortic dissection, as it can increase the risk of bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitroglycerin (GTN)\u003C/strong\u003E can cause vasodilation and reduce blood pressure, but it is not the first-line therapy for aortic dissection. It can be considered if blood pressure remains elevated despite beta-blockade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium channel blockers\u003C/strong\u003E are not recommended for the acute management of aortic dissection, as they can increase the risk of reflex tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aortic dissection is an emergency and medical therapy should be commenced promptly.","Beta-blockers are the first-line treatment to reduce heart rate and blood pressure in aortic dissection."],"references":["Levy D, Goyal A, Grigorova Y, et al. Aortic Dissection. [Updated 2022 May 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441963/","Nickson, C. Acute Aortic Dissection. March 2023 [Internet]. Accessed on 8 Jan 2025.  Available from: https://litfl.com/acute-aortic-dissection/","Smedberg C, Hultgren R, Leander K, Steuer J. Pharmacological treatment in patients with aortic dissection. Open Heart. 2022 Nov;9(2):e002082. doi: 10.1136/openhrt-2022-002082. PMID: 36396295; PMCID: PMC9677041. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9677041/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96981"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12545"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions